The paper deals with the computational complexity of detecting binary linear codes, which is a problem in information theory (cs.IT). The problem involves finding the minimum distance between a set of noisy codeword observations and a set of candidate linear codes, which can be formulated as a combinatorial optimization problem (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the NP-hardness of the problem, which is a topic in computational complexity theory (cs.CC). Additionally, the paper identifies open questions related to the code detection problem, which can be seen as a topic in discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and machine learning (cs.SI).
